Description.LocalizedString: The kids were confused, and Adam explained that this game wasn't about winning or losing.
He described a gang of goblins and asked the students what they wanted to do. A scrawny girl suggested they fight.
Soon the kids were caught up in the game, carefully planning their next steps. Adam sat back in his chair and smiled.
The players' handbook described a role called the "Artificer", makers of magical items. Gabriel kept reading.
The game seemed to require long hours, but he could imagine how much fun it would be to plan and play.
His break ended, Gabriel collected his tools and returned to the engine bay to finish his repairs.

The game ended early, leaving plenty of time for Elodie and her friends to have their own real-life adventure.
The DM briefly mentioned that the local governor was suspected of stealing taxpayer money. Zarina felt a surge of excitement.
While the rest of the party entered the dungeon, Zarina declared her rogue would break into the Governor's Manor.
The DM was quick on her feet, and Zarina later rejoined the party with proof of the Governor's corruption.

In an instant, an entire pack was upon her, snapping at her heels, wrists, and throat as she fought them off one by one.
She cut them down until only one was left. It ran for the trees, but fell in a heap when she threw her axe into its back.

She ignored her mother's horrified scream as she leaned forward and slid down the roof.

He crawled, half-blind from sand in his eyes. In his darkest moments he heard the screaming, echoes from his memory.
He was just a kid, but he had survived where they did not. Growing old had been both a blessing and a curse.
As his eyes cleared, something flipped him onto his back. He wailed at the sight of those he'd left behind, back to reclaim him.
Her beauty was the object of obsession, and many were driven mad by her influence.
Her body had been torn to pieces countless times. And every time, those pieces grew into her duplicates.
Whether she was human or a monster, she would do anything to get what she wanted.
She could unhinge her monstrous jaw to make sure she got the juiciest bite.
She would hunt her prey and cherish their torment, finding pleasure in their pain.
The last thing her victims often heard was her joyous, hungry laugh.
He crept down the stairs. Flashlight in hand, he hopped the backyard fence and crept up to his neighbor's shed.
The shed was scary, but he knew the neighbors kept the presents in there. Sure enough, he found a pile of wrapped gifts inside.
Smiling, he grabbed a nearby boxcutter and ripped open all the presents. It was his favorite Christmas memory.
Despite his uncle's warnings, Talbot was drawn to the bright red berries. When no one was looking, he ate a few.
The forest darkened and panicked figures fled in all directions. He tried to chase after them, but soon everything went black.
He awoke in bed to find a cool towel on his forehead, his mother soothing him as he trembled from the frightful dream.
